<h3>Pinterest and Google SEO Working Together</h3>
<p>Pinterest Pins appear in Google Image search and sometimes in standard Google results. This creates a dual-ranking opportunity.</p>
<p>A blog post optimized for Google targets "modern kitchen remodel ideas." The same blog post generates 3 to 5 Pinterest Pins targeting the same keyword. The blog post ranks on Google. The Pins rank on Pinterest Search. Both drive traffic to the same page.</p>
<p>The compounding effect: a blog post that ranks on Google AND has 5 Pins ranking on Pinterest generates traffic from 2 search engines simultaneously. This is why content-driven businesses that use both channels together outperform those using either one alone.</p>
<p>Link every Pin to a page on your website. Not to your homepage. To the specific blog post, product page, or landing page the Pin represents. Pinterest evaluates the linked page content for relevance signals. An <a href="/blog/on-page-seo-guide/">on-page optimized</a> landing page strengthens the Pin's ranking in Pinterest Search.</p>
